</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DC40C0BE98017EED9A3EFF1C64EBEC8E" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="4028D763B1399C10C0BBDDFFC850CF94" pageNumber="12">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6E3B22E0089B9AE72C4AF2E0F5496847" pageNumber="12">
All species of 
<taxonomicName id="1A2A3390095E42B6C9160E0BB06CEC39" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Ophthalmolebias">Ophthalmolebias</taxonomicName>
except 
<taxonomicName id="1D97BADE487477942E0AC63437C4B65E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="constanciae">S. constanciae</taxonomicName>
are endemic to the area of eastern Brazil between rio Cachoeira and rio Pardo basins, Estado da Bahia, in a rain forest region. 
<taxonomicName id="CBB110BDF0CD4D95E70B271A354FABF5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="constanciae">Simpsonichthys constanciae</taxonomicName>
is endemic to the plains adjacent to the lower rio 
<normalizedToken id="AB4B46B309506EC100268C408DB4FACD" originalValue="S達o">Sao</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken id="1C5F557B698630E1F6B0D4B180252DDB" originalValue="Jo達o">Joao</normalizedToken>
, Estado do Rio de Janeiro, a semi-arid coastal zone.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AE0E323571FEF81D755C5CE2CC7DD527" pageNumber="13">
<pageStartToken id="2A0BD834DD5DC37780436BA4D48A3E09" pageNumber="13">No</pageStartToken>
species of 
<taxonomicName id="9A8294533F29000EF5E3FF26ED94F8BA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Ophthalmolebias">Ophthalmolebias</taxonomicName>
is known to occur in the broad area between the rio Pardo and rio 
<normalizedToken id="CF6C1EE80546003C8A1127135711283F" originalValue="S達o">Sao</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken id="285D514B1121B38B9FDC58BE8B8FD9A2" originalValue="Jo達o">Joao</normalizedToken>
basins (Fig. 4).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
